Rating: 1
Ok lets, get real, I am Hispanic, and NEVER in my entire life have I ever encountered salsa in Albondigas. And yes I have had several variations, some Mexican moms like to add rice to the meatball itself, but always, vegetables are kept to a minimum, the whole emphasis is the rice and meatball, everything else is very secondary. Also, just try finding bulk pork sausage in a mexican Grocery store, its not exactly a best seller, and its not often used for Albondigas. And as for putting salsa in your Albondigas, well, that would be the equivalent of putting cheese dip or spinach dip into your soup. Also, "heat" has nothing to do with Albondigas, we make this dish for our babies to eat when they are ill, its comfort food. Chorizo is generally a breakfast item, however, its also used as a stuffing and side dish as well. Again, none of the many Mexican moms I know have ever used it to make Albondigas. Perhaps this recipe was introduced by someone hoping to "update" or put a spin on the original, but some things are better left unchanged. I hope this is helpful for those of you looking to make authentic Albondigas.

